instruction: How do I make an appointment to see an advisor?
output: You may make an appointment with any ECE advisor through AdvisorLink (advisor.gatech.edu). Check the calendars for available time slots and verify the appointment is in the office (Van Leer 208) or online.

instruction: Can I just come to the office without an appointment? I just have a quick question.
output: No walk-ins are allowed. You must make an appointment to see an ECE undergraduate academic advisor. You may always email your advisor or the undergraduate office:   undergraduate@ece.gatech.edu

instruction: How do I know which threads to pick?
output:
Explore each thread and see which two are most interesting to you and are related to your plans after graduation.  Each thread gives a depth of information and a sample of career paths. (Mention in ECE1100)
https://www.ece.gatech.edu/curriculum-threads
How to add threads:
https://degreeworks.gatech.edu/files/concentration_mgt.pd

instruction: Where can I get help making my 4-year academic plan for graduation?
output:
ECE has provided 8-semester plans for every thread combination for both the BSEE and BSCMPE degrees.
https://ece.gatech.edu/electrical-engineering-threads-semester-plans
https://ece.gatech.edu/computer-engineering-threads-semester-plans

instruction: How do I change my major?
output:
Complete the change of major form for undergraduate students through the Registrars DocuSign application. The form goes to the new major school first and then your current major to be approved and signed by each majors advisor.
https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/change-major-form-undergraduate-students_ds

instruction: How does a transfer student outside of ECE change his/her major to EE or CMPE?
output:
Non-majors must be enrolled for at least one semester at Georgia Tech.
Students must have a minimum GPA of 2.70.
Must meet the Georgia Tech Admissions requirements for EE and CMPE. Students must have completed CHEM 1310/1211K, CS 1301, ENGL 1101 and 1102, MATH 1551 and 1552, and PHYS 2211.
https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/change-major-form-undergraduate-students_ds

instruction: How do I declare a minor?
output:
Most minors are approved by sending the minor form through DocuSign to be signed by the minor school and your major school.
Some minors require an additional application:  Computer Science, Engineering and Business, Robotics
CMPE majors following the thread curriculum are not eligible to pursue a minor in CS.
Information for Undergraduate Minors: 
https://catalog.gatech.edu/academics/minors/
Minor form:  https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/change-minor-form_ds
Students may not graduate with an incomplete minor on their record. If you do not plan to complete the minor, submit the same form (link above) to remove the minor.

instruction: What is the minimum GPA required to meet degree requirements?
output: Students must earn a C or better in all CS, MATH, PHYS and ECE required courses. Additionally, students must earn a C or better in any required courses from a thread. Georgia Tech requires a minimum GPA of 2.0 to graduate.

instruction: What courses can I take pass-fail?
output:
ECE allows its students to take humanities, social sciences (except the ECON requirement), science elective for EE majors, and approved/free electives as pass-fail. The course must be offered on a pass-fail basis.
https://catalog.gatech.edu/policies/grading-gpa/pass-fail-system-rules/
ECE 1100 and ECE 3005 are two required courses for the thread curriculum and are only offered on a pass-fail basis.  These count for 2 hours toward a students pass-fail allowance.
During phase 1 and phase 2 registration, students may change the basis of a course through the Buzzport accounts. After phase 2 until the mid-semester drop day, you must send ECE a grade mode change form to be approved and signed.
https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/grade-mode-change-form

instruction: How does research count toward my degree?
output:
Students may use up to 6 hours of research (special problems, research section, or VIP) toward FREE electives. If a student decides on the research option (completing a thesis), then ECE will allow 9 hours of research to count toward the degree. In this case, 3 hours of ECE 4699 may apply to one EE thread elective requiring an ECE 3000/4000 level elective and 6 hours may apply to FREE electives.
Students who complete a 2-semester research project, ECE 3951/3952 or ECE 4951/4952, may apply these 3 hours to an EE thread requiring an ECE 3000/4000 level elective. The max hours allowed of research for two threads is 3 hours.
https://ece.gatech.edu/ece-undergraduate-docusign-forms
https://vip.gatech.edu/

instruction: What is the grade substitution policy?
output:
A student who earns an unsatisfactory grade in a course (D or F) may repeat that course within a year and submit a grade substitution form. The initial grade continues to appear on the GT transcript, but the quality points will no longer be averaged into your GT GPA. Students may use a grade sub twice throughout their undergraduate academic career.
Policy:  https://catalog.gatech.edu/policies/grading-gpa/grade-substitution/
Form:  https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/grade-substitution-form

instruction: What are my options to complete senior design?
output:
There are 3 pathways for EE and CMPE majors.
1)The two-semester ECE team project: Students work with their same team for 2 consecutive semesters on an ECE project. You can do this series either fall-spring or spring-fall. Current course numbers are ECE 4871 and ECE 4872.
2)Single semester ECE team project: Students work with a team for 1 semester on an ECE project. The current course number is ECE 4873. The prerequisite for this course is ECE 3011, which only counts as a FREE elective.
3)Single semester multidisciplinary team project: Students work with a team for 1 semester on a multidisciplinary project. The current course number is ECE 4723. The prerequisite for this course is ECE 3011, which only counts as a FREE elective.

instruction: How do I request a permit for an ECE course?
output:
Please make a request during registration through the ECE Permit System:
https://secure.ece.gatech.edu/overloads_permits/
ECE will receive and review all requests and respond in a timely manner. Due to helping our current load of students and monitoring permit requests, your patience during registration is appreciated.

instruction: I need to miss class and need an approved absence. How do I get one?
output:
An approved absence can be granted for a students participation in an institutes activity (ex: field trips, athletic events). This request will be approved by the Student Academic and Financial Affairs Committee of the Academic Senate. Contact the Registrars office for the form:
https://registrar.gatech.edu/info/institute-approved-absence-form-for-students

Registration questions:  https://registrar.gatech.edu/registration
Academic calendar :  https://registrar.gatech.edu/calendar
Financial aid: https://finaid.gatech.edu
Campus forms:  https://registrar.gatech.edu/forms
Student Engagement and Well Being: https://sewb.ece.gatech.edu/

instruction: What technical interest groups (tracks) are included in ECE?
output:
ECE's faculty is organized into 11 technical interest groups (TIGs) that collectively represent the major research thrusts of the School and technical interest areas of courses. These areas are highly interrelated, and many faculty members engage in research in multiple TIGs. Following is a brief description of each TIG, with a bulleted list of their major areas of research. 
Bioegineering: Bioengineering applies engineering principles to study, manipulate, and control biological processes. In this area, mathematical, physical, and engineering concepts are developed and applied to solve problems in medicine and biology through hardware and software including electronics, sensors, engineering systems, data processing, computational imaging, machine learning, and artificial intelligence.
Computer Systems and Software: Computer Systems and Software creates novel computing environments for edge, cloud, and high-performance computing. Designs span low-power, reconfigurable microarchitectures to integrated hardware/software systems to large-scale distributed software and internetworked devices that communicate, learn, and intelligently adapt to the environment. Activities focus on optimizing cross-cutting characteristics, such as power/energy consumption, resiliency, and security.
Digital Signal Processing: Digital Signal Processing (DSP) involves the representation, processing, modeling, and analysis of signals, information, and physical phenomena. DSP interprets the captured data and enables visualization, analysis, manipulation, and control. DSP lies at the core of modern artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning algorithms.
Electrical Energy: Electrical Energy is primarily concerned with meeting the demand for electric energy in a safe, reliable, secure, cost-effective, and environmentally friendly manner.
Electromagnetics: Electromagnetics includes everything about radio waves: their generation, propagation, and interactions with materials, devices, and systems.
Electronic Design and Applications: Electronic Design and Applications focuses on device and integrated circuit fabrication, circuit and system design and simulation, and instrumentation and testing techniques.
Nanotechnology: Nanotechnology is concerned with the emerging of enabling nano-scale materials and devices, including the design, analysis, and realization of enabling systems.
Optics and Photonics: Optics and Photonics focuses on the exploitation of light waves and photons for communication, signal processing, imaging, sensing, computing, lighting, and energy harvesting.
Systems and Controls: Systems and Controls is concerned with mathematical and computational techniques for modeling, estimation, and control of systems and processes.
Telecommunications: Telecommunications focuses on the characterization, representation, transmission, storage, and networking of information over various media including space, optical fiber, and cable.
VLSI Systems and Digital Design: VLSI Systems and Digital Design involves designing and testing complex digital and mixed-signal electronic systems. These techniques optimize power, performance, and reliability metrics across a wide range of applications.

instruction: What is the academic requirement for the M.S.E.C.E. non-thesis option?
output: The academic requirements for the M.S.E.C.E. non-thesis option include Group I, Group II, and Group III courses, with a total of 30 hours required. Group I requires nine graduate-level ECE hours, Group II requires nine additional ECE graduate-level hours (at least six outside the chosen technical area), and Group III comprises nine elective hours, including a mandatory course in Technology Entrepreneurship.

instruction: How many hours are required for the M.S.E.C.E. thesis option?
output: The M.S.E.C.E. thesis option requires a total of 30 hours. This includes six hours in Group I, six hours in Group II, and three hours in Group III. Additionally, there are 12 hours dedicated to Thesis research, including Responsible Conduct of Research (RCR).

instruction: What are the key requirements for the Joint B.S./M.S. degree program?
output: To be eligible for the Joint B.S./M.S. degree program, students must be enrolled as undergraduate students in the ECE program. The program allows students to receive both a bachelor of science in electrical engineering or computer engineering and a masters degree in electrical and computer engineering within a five-year time frame. Qualified students may receive GRA/GTA appointments with stipends and reduced tuition, and up to six credit hours of senior/graduate-level ECE coursework can be used for both degrees.

instruction: How can students qualify for the benefits of the Joint B.S./M.S. program?
output: To qualify for the benefits of the Joint B.S./M.S. program, students must have a final cumulative GPA of 3.5 or higher. They may receive application fee waivers, GRE requirement waivers, and GRA/GTA appointments with stipends and reduced tuition. Additionally, students with a GPA of 3.5 or higher can move up to 12 hours forward from the BS program to the MS program, with six of these hours counted for both degrees.

instruction: What are the deadlines for official graduate applications to the MS program in the Joint B.S./M.S. program?
output: For the Atlanta Campus, the deadline for the Fall graduating semester (for following Spring start of BS/MS program) is September 15, and for the Spring and Summer graduating semesters (for following Fall start of BS/MS program), it is May 1. The deadlines are the same for Distance Learning, Shenzhen, and Europe campuses.

instruction: What are the steps to maintain eligibility for the BS/MS program after being accepted?
output: To maintain eligibility for the BS/MS program after being accepted, students must complete the BS degree first and then matriculate into the MS program. They cannot graduate with both degrees simultaneously. Students should start the MS program immediately after graduating with their BS degree, with the exception of summer semester. Graduating with a GPA of 3.5 or higher is also a requirement, and students must complete their MS degree within two years of graduating with the BS degree.

instruction: How can B.S./M.S. students pursue doctoral studies in ECE?
output: B.S./M.S. students are welcome to pursue doctoral studies in ECE. There are differences in coursework requirements between the M.S. and Ph.D. degrees. Students planning to pursue the Ph.D. can save time by choosing M.S. classes with Ph.D. requirements in mind. For more details, students can visit the Ph.D. Degrees page and explore the 'Change Major from M.S. to Ph.D.' section at the bottom of the page.

instruction: can you tell me more about this course:
